The White House held a Conference on Bullying Prevention, which brought together students, parents, teachers, non-profit leaders, advocates, and policymakers to address the issue of bullying. The conference included opening remarks from President Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama, followed by a conversation with experts on effective programs and policies to prevent bullying. Breakout sessions were held to discuss in-school policies, in-school programs, community-based programs, cyberbullying, and campus-based programs. Additionally, there were live chats with Facebook and iVillage to engage audiences across the country. The conference concluded with closing remarks from Secretary of Health and Human Services Kathleen Sebelius, Secretary of Education Arne Duncan, and White House Domestic Policy Advisor Melody Barnes.